Documentary exploring the rise and fall of the most visionary period in
British music history: five kaleidoscopic years between 1965 and 1970
when a handful of dreamers reimagined pop music.

When a generation of British R&B bands discovered LSD, conventions were
questioned. From out of the bohemian underground and into the pop
mainstream, the psychedelic era produced some of the most ground-breaking
music ever made, pioneered by young improvising bands like Soft Machine
and Pink Floyd, then quickly taken to the charts by the likes of the Beatles
Procol Harum, the Small Faces and the Moody Blues, even while being reimagined
in the country by bucolic, folk-based artists like the Incredible String Band
and Vashti Bunyan.

The film is narrated by Nigel Planer with contributions and freshly-shot
performances from artists who lived and breathed the psych revolution
Paul McCartney, Ginger Baker, Robert Wyatt, Roy Wood, the Zombies, Mike Heron
Vashti Bunyan, Joe Boyd, Gary Brooker, Arthur Brown, Kenney Jones, Barry Miles
the Pretty Things and the Moody Blues.
